ce:section.ce:para:
Cell viability assay is an indispensable parameter for further application of the nitrogen-doped CNDs, such as bioimaging and live cell-labeling [50]. For the as-prepared CNDs, no obvious cell viability decrease was observed. Even at a high concentration of 600μgml−1 the cell viability was still greater than 95%, for all tasted cell lines, after a long period of incubation (Fig. S9 of Supplementary material). Statistical analysis of the results showed that no statistical differences, between samples and control were found, at P<
                        0.01. Moreover, no changes in cell morphology were observed, bespeaking good biocompatibility of the CNDs. Therefore, CNDs concentration up to 600μgml−1 can be safely administered to cells. Because of their low cytotoxicity, CNDs have the potential for bioimaging applications. To test their applicability, cells were incubated with the bright CNDs and they were observed using fluorescence microscopy. The results showed that the CNDs entered the cells and they are located at the perinuclear region, making feasible their observation under UV-light, as compared to the non-treated cells (Fig. 9
                        ). Overall, due to their aforementioned merits and low cytotocixity, CNDs from apple seeds can be used for in-vitro imaging and have potential for other biological applications.
